d to rule the performance roost, but the Fairlane-based Torino was another =
fast offering during its time on the market. <em>MotorTrend</em> named the =
    <span class=3D"display-card-hyperlink-article" data-id=3D"1009061"><a h=
ref=3D"https://www.hotcars.com/heres-what-gearheads-should-know-about-the-f=
ord-torino-cobra/" target=3D"_blank">Torino Cobra</a></span> its Car of The=
 Year for 1970, and that's for good reason. While the Ford looked unassumin=
g on the outside, it was a born supercar slayer under the hood.    </p>    =
<p>Powering the was a 429-cubic-inch 385-series big block V8, producing 360=
 horsepower in Thunder Jet guise, 370 horsepower in Cobra Jet guise, and 37=
5 horsepower if you checked the Drag Pack option and went for the Super Cob=
ra Jet. With a four-speed manual transmission and a set of 3.91 gears, <a h=
ref=3D"https://www.hemmings.com/stories/the-unassuming-supercar-slayer-1970=
-ford-torino-cobra/" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank"><em>Moto=
rTrend</em> achieved a 13.99 E.T.</a> at 101 mph in a middling Cobra Jet du=
ring a roundup of Ford's 1970 Torino models. As if that wasn't impressive e=
nough, 60 mph came in a mere 5.8 seconds.</p>    <!-- No AdsNinja v10 Clien=
