rmuseum.org/1970-plymouth-superbird/" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" target=3D=
"_blank">direct aim of luring Richard Petty</a> to come back from the Ford =
team, and it's an exercise that yielded a truly impressive performance car.=
 Beyond its success in NASCAR racing, the     <span class=3D"display-card-h=
yperlink-article" data-id=3D"1032080"><a href=3D"https://www.hotcars.com/fe=
atures-that-make-plymouth-superbird-rare-iconic-muscle-car/" target=3D"_bla=
nk">Plymouth Superbird</a></span> established itself as a formidable threat=
 on the street. In making the base     <span class=3D"display-card-hyperlin=
k-article" data-id=3D"1019883"><a href=3D"https://www.hotcars.com/a-look-ba=
ck-at-the-1970-plymouth-road-runner-superbird/" target=3D"_blank">Road Runn=
er</a></span> more aerodynamic, Plymouth added a long, sloping nosecone and=
 a distinctive 23-inch rear spoiler.    </p>    <p>The design borrowed from=
 the     <span class=3D"display-card-hyperlink-article" data-id=3D"31823"><=
a href=3D"https://www.hotcars.com/dodge-charger-daytona-plymouth-superbird-=
facts/" target=3D"_blank">Charger Daytona</a></span> that came before it in=
 1969, but Plymouth stylists wanted to improve the aesthetic appeal. Ignori=
ng the wind-tunnel-tested shapes, they altered the nose cone and sloped the=
 tail, ultimately to the detriment of the Superbird's top speed. <a href=3D=
"https://www.roadandtrack.com/car-culture/a33108/the-plymouth-superbird-was=
-actually-slower-than-the-dodge-charger-daytona/" rel=3D"noopener noreferre=
r" target=3D"_blank">According to period testing</a>, the Plymouth was actu=
ally slower than the Dodge by anywhere from 1-3 mph, all other factors bein=
g equal.    </p>    <!-- No AdsNinja v10 Client! --><h2 id=3D"1970-buick-gs=
