<p>The GS455 Stage 1 ranks among the most     <span class=3D"display-card-h=
yperlink-article" data-id=3D"1013911"><a href=3D"https://www.hotcars.com/wh=
y-the-buick-skylark-is-a-forgotten-muscle-car/" target=3D"_blank">underappr=
eciated muscle cars</a></span> of the era, and the subsequent GSX was intro=
duced as a means to shake things up with a more eye-catching appearance. St=
ill, despite its sleeper qualities, the Buick isn't an option to be overloo=
ked. <em>MotorTrend</em> accomplished a 13.38-second quarter mile at 105 mp=
h in a 1969 test, earning the <a href=3D"https://www.hotrod.com/features/fi=
rst-stage-flyer-september-1988-982-1398-88-1/" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer" =
target=3D"_blank">GS455 the honor</a> of =E2=80=9CThe Quickest American Pro=
duction Muscle Car=E2=80=9D for 1970.    </p>    <p>Like many manufacturers=
 back in the day, Buick probably misquoted the performance in order to keep=
 insurance agents happy. Claimed output came to 360 horsepower and 510 lb-f=
t of torque, though this only made for a 10-hp improvement over the standar=
d 455. In reality, the Stage 1 was <a href=3D"https://www.audrainautomuseum=
.org/more-than-just-american-muscle/1971-buick-gsx-stage-1-coupe" rel=3D"no=
opener noreferrer" target=3D"_blank">likely to push 400 horses or more</a>,=
 so it's no wonder that it was able to achieve a 6-second 0-60 mph time and=
 a top speed of 115.</p>           =20
